arch:property.oc:show_val: L25 is slope wash that continues below L16. The fill is consistent with the fill in L16 but is a slightly different color so we changed locus. Upon closer examination, L16 and L25 are the same fill, therefore they are equal. At the south 1 meter of the locus we came upon some mixed ashy fill and picked up a kiln stand, KT25 at the SW corner before closing the locus and opening L35 below. We left the other 3 meters to the north open until we decide to move more fill. We kept the last 4 meters of L25 open until we closed the trench because it was still part of the eroded fill.
compacted clayey loam with coarse and fine particles mixed
this fill has areas which are more compacted at the south end and looser on the north end, there was lots of pottery.

arch:note.arch:string: Contexts excavated in trenches were recorded using the "locus system." A locus is any discrete three-dimensional entity excavated in a trench. The key to the locus system is the recognition that a locus is any one thing. Differences in soil composition or texture are therefore as important as, for example, the difference between a pit and a wall. If two entities were distinct, they were considered separate loci and were therefore assigned separate locus numbers. It should also be noted that every context excavated in a trench was given a locus number and thus the trench itself is made up completely of excavated loci.
